      <timing>
        <reasoning>
          Temporal cues in the passage are explicit and implicit. The opening line gives a clear anchor: "Three weeks since the battle." The scene then describes a single day of active building, testing, and socializing: Runner demonstrates acoustic chambers, Velvet tests seating, Remedy experiments with scents, Holloway calls a break, and the group settles down — all implying a workday that begins in the morning or early day and runs through the afternoon into evening. The passage ends the same day with Buddy detecting an external signal, which instantly changes the group's mood. 

          Given those cues, the passage covers roughly one full workday of activity that takes place three weeks after the previous passage ended (~17:30). During the 3-week gap, reasonable events include recovery work, structural repairs, redesign planning, iterative prototyping (acoustic chambers, seating, scent compounds), and social reintegration — all of which the text describes as having already occurred. No major implausibilities are present: plants with regenerative/growth capabilities, coordinated labor, and concentrated effort from a small community make visible redesign and substantial comfort-focused modifications within three weeks believable. The only minor note is that the level of finish described (comfortable, well-integrated spaces across multiple sections) is on the faster side but still plausible given nonhuman growth rates and full-group labor. The final abrupt shift (human-signal detection) is temporally immediate and fits narratively as the closing beat of the scene.
        </reasoning>
        <starts>~21 days after previous passage (three weeks after the battle); during daytime (approx. 09:00–11:00)</starts>
        <ends>Same day, late afternoon/early evening (approx. 17:00–18:30)</ends>
        <gap-from-previous>Three weeks (about 21 days). During that gap: removal of hostile node residues, structural stabilization, iterative rebuilding and prototyping (acoustic chambers, seating, scent compounds), social reintegration and trust-building exercises, and collective planning. Essentially the recovery and redesign work that the passage shows already completed.</gap-from-previous>
        <plausibility>Plausible. Three weeks is a reasonable interval for a motivated, cooperative group—especially one with plant growth and regeneration capabilities—to stabilize damage and prototype comfortable, integrated community spaces. The single-day slice of activity (testing, adjustments, a break, and then the signal arriving) is also internally consistent. If the author wants absolute realism, they could slow the pace slightly or add a line acknowledging ongoing unfinished work in farther wings, but nothing in the passage creates a major temporal contradiction.</plausibility>
